The '''Alvin W. Vogtle Electric Generating Plant''', also known as '''Plant Vogtle''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|v|oʊ|g|əl}} {{respell|VOH|gəl}}),<ref>{{cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=POW86gZXC8Q |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116145732/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=POW86gZXC8Q&gl=US&hl=en |archive-date=January 16, 2014 |url-status=bot: unknown |title=Inside the Nuclear Energy Renaissance: Plant Vogtle |publisher=Southern Company |date=January 7, 2014 |access-date=May 26, 2017 |via=YouTube }}</ref> is a four-unit [[nuclear power plant]] located in [[Burke County, Georgia|Burke County]], near [[Waynesboro, Georgia|Waynesboro]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], in the [[southeastern United States]]. With a power capacity of 4,536 [[watt|megawatts]], it is the largest nuclear power plant in the United States (as of 2025), after Units 3 & 4 began operating.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Granholm |first=Jennifer |date=2024-05-31 |title=Remarks as Delivered by Secretary Jennifer M. Granholm on Startup of Vogtle Unit 4 and Growth of U.S. Nuclear Industry |url=https://www.energy.gov/articles/remarks-delivered-secretary-jennifer-m-granholm-startup-vogtle-unit-4-and-growth-us |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240604100349/https://www.energy.gov/articles/remarks-delivered-secretary-jennifer-m-granholm-startup-vogtle-unit-4-and-growth-us |archive-date=2024-06-04 |access-date=2024-06-04 |website=Department of Energy}}</ref> It is also the only nuclear plant in the country with four reactors. It is named after a former [[Alabama Power]] and [[Southern Company]] board chairman, [[Alvin Vogtle]].

The first two units are [[Westinghouse Electric Company|Westinghouse]] [[pressurized water reactor]]s (PWR), with a [[General Electric]] [[steam turbine]] and [[electric generator]]. Units&nbsp;1&nbsp;and&nbsp;2 were completed in 1987 and 1989, respectively, and have a gross electricity generation capacity of 1,215&nbsp;MW, for a combined capacity of 2,430&nbsp;MW.<ref name="southernco">{{cite web  | title=Plant Vogtle - Southern Company  | publisher=Southern Company  | url=http://www.southernco.com/southernnuclear/vogtle.asp  | access-date= March 2, 2007 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070205113659/http://www.southernco.com/southernnuclear/vogtle.asp <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archive-date = February 5, 2007}}</ref> The twin natural-draft [[cooling towers]] are {{convert|548|ft|m|abbr=on}} tall and provide cooling to the plant's main condensers. 
Four smaller mechanical draft cooling towers provide nuclear service cooling water (NSCW) to safety and auxiliary non-safety components, as well as remove the [[decay heat]] from the reactor when the plant is offline. One natural-draft tower and two NSCW towers serve each unit. In 2009, the [[Nuclear Regulatory Commission]] (NRC) renewed the licenses for both units for an additional 20&nbsp;years<ref>{{cite news| url= http://chronicle.augusta.com/stories/2009/06/04/met_526417.shtml| title= Licenses for Vogtle current reactors renewed| last= Pavey | first= Rob | date= June 4, 2009 | work= [[Augusta Chronicle]] | access-date= June 5, 2009}}</ref> to January 16, 2047 for Unit 1,<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.nrc.gov/info-finder/reactors/vog1.html |title= Vogtle Electric Generating Plant, Unit 1 |date= February 10, 2017 |work= NRC |publisher= [[Nuclear Regulatory Commission]] |access-date= March 18, 2018 }}</ref> and September 2, 2049 for Unit 2.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.nrc.gov/info-finder/reactors/vog2.html |title= Vogtle Electric Generating Plant, Unit 1 |date= February 10, 2017 |work= NRC |publisher= [[Nuclear Regulatory Commission]] |access-date= March 18, 2018 }}</ref><ref name="construction">{{cite news|last=Gertner|first=Jon|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/07/16/magazine/16nuclear.html|newspaper= [[The New York Times]]|title= Atomic Balm?|date=July 16, 2006}}</ref> During the construction of Vogtle's first two units, capital investment required jumped from an estimated $660&nbsp;million to $8.87&nbsp;billion.<ref name="doe">{{cite web  |last=Moens  |first=John  |title=U.S. Nuclear Plants - Vogtle  |publisher=[[Energy Information Administration]], [[U.S. Department of Energy]]  |date=March 18, 2005 |url=http://www.eia.doe.gov/cneaf/nuclear/page/at_a_glance/reactors/vogtle.html  |access-date=March 2, 2007  |url-status=dead  |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010208074946/http://www.eia.doe.gov/cneaf/nuclear/page/at_a_glance/reactors/vogtle.html  |archive-date=February 8, 2001   }}</ref> (${{format price|{{Inflation|US-GDP|8.87e9|1989}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US-GDP}} dollars{{Inflation-fn|US-GDP}})

Two additional units utilizing [[Westinghouse AP1000]] reactors began preliminary construction in 2009, with Unit 3 being completed in July 2023.<ref name="unit3beginscnbc" /><ref>{{cite news| url= http://chronicle.augusta.com/stories/2009/11/22/bus_556611.shtml| title= Vogtle lays groundwork for first U.S. reactors in decades| last= Pavey | first= Rob | date= November 22, 2009 | work= [[Augusta Chronicle]] | access-date= October 22, 2009}}</ref> Natural-draft type cooling towers were also selected, and the two new cooling towers are nearly {{convert|600|ft|m|abbr=on}} tall. During construction, the units suffered several delays and cost overruns. The certified construction and capital costs for these two new units were originally $14 billion, according to the Seventeenth Semi-annual Vogtle Construction Monitoring Report in 2017.<ref name="17thReport">{{cite news|url=http://www.psc.state.ga.us/factsv2/Document.aspx?documentNumber=169459|publisher= [[Georgia Power]]|title=Seventeenth Semi-Annual Construction Monitoring Report for Plant Vogtle Units 3 and 4.|date=August 2017}}</ref> This last report blames the latest increase in costs on the contractor not completing work as scheduled. Another complicating factor in the construction process is the bankruptcy of Westinghouse in 2017.<ref name=retuers-rb>{{cite news|url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-toshiba-accounting-board-idUSKBN17006K |title= Toshiba's Westinghouse files for bankruptcy as charges jump |website= [[reuters.com]] |first1= Makiko |last1= Yamazaki |first2= Tim |last2= Kelly |date= March 29, 2017 |access-date=March 29, 2017}}</ref>
In 2018, costs were estimated to be about $25 billion.<ref name=power-eng-20180809/> By 2021, they were estimated to be over $28.5 billion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.augustachronicle.com/story/news/2021/11/04/georgia-power-nuclear-reactors-plant-vogtle-cost-doubles-energy-costs/6286729001/|title='Outrageous' price tag: Plant Vogtle cost doubles to $28.5 billion as other owners balk|website=The Augusta Chronicle|accessdate=July 28, 2023}}</ref> In 2023, costs had increased to $34 billion, with work still to be completed on Vogtle 4.<ref name="auto1"/>

Unit 3 began commercial operations on July 31, 2023, becoming the first new nuclear reactor in the United States in 7 years.<ref name="unit3beginscnbc">{{cite news |last1=Clifford |first1=Catherine |title=America's first new nuclear reactor in nearly seven years starts operations |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2023/07/31/vogtle-unit-3-nuclear-reactor-long-delayed-starts-delivering-power.html |access-date=4 August 2023 |work=CNBC |date=31 July 2023}}</ref> Unit 4 entered commercial operation on April 29, 2024.<ref name=":2" />

As of the reported FY 2024 3rd quarter financial statements, for units 3-4, the net capital costs incurred by Georgia Power was $10.65 billion in total, with an additional estimated $83 million in completion costs related to site demobilization. This is inclusive of $1.2 billion not shared with other Vogtle owners, net of ~$1.9 billion received from Toshiba in settlement and related customer refunds. With Georgia Power's 45.7% ownership interest implying a total capitalized construction cost of $23.76 billion for Unit 3-4. This is not inclusive of the non-capitalized financing charges incurred (interest) totaling $3.53 billion by Georgia Power, as this was recovered via ratepayer surcharges before completion.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://s27.q4cdn.com/273397814/files/doc_financials/2024/q3/7b5aa5c3-65a1-46f4-a186-b63385f82e11.pdf | title=FORM 10-Q | website=s27.q4cdn.com}}</ref>

==Units 1 and 2==
{{more citations needed section|date=December 2025}}
Vogtle units 1 and 2 are a set of identical Westinghouse 4-Loop reactors. Like many North American nuclear power stations, each of the Vogtle units are constructed of a steel-lined, prestressed, post-tensioned
concrete cylinder with a hemispherical dome. The containment was designed by the Los Angeles Regional Office of the [[Bechtel Corporation]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.nrc.gov/docs/ML1633/ML16330A389.pdf | title=Final Safety Analysis Report (FSAR) - Vogtle Electric Generating Plant | website=www.nrc.gov}}</ref>

===Power Uprate===

In 2008, reactors 1 and 2 were increased in power by 1.7% by an "Appendix&nbsp;K" uprate,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrc.gov/reading-rm/doc-collections/cfr/part050/part050-appk.html|title=NRC: 10 CFR Appendix K to Part 50—ECCS Evaluation Models|website=www.nrc.gov}}</ref> also called a Measurement Uncertainty Recapture (MUR) uprate. Measurement uncertainty recapture power uprates are less than 2&nbsp;percent, and are achieved by implementing enhanced techniques for calculating reactor power. This involves the use of state-of-the-art feedwater flow measurement devices to more precisely measure feedwater flow, which is used to calculate reactor power.<ref name="auto">{{cite web|url=https://www.nrc.gov/reactors/operating/licensing/power-uprates.html|title=NRC: Power Uprates|website=www.nrc.gov}}</ref>

More precise measurements reduce the degree of uncertainty in the power level, which is used by analysts to predict the ability of the reactor to be safely shut down under postulated accident conditions.<ref name="auto"/> Because the reactor power can be calculated with much greater accuracy than with the older [[Venturi effect|venturi]] type measurement, the plant can safely run within a tighter margin of error to its limits. The newer [[ultrasonic flowmeter]] works by comparing the time it takes [[Ultrasound|ultrasonic]] sound pulses to travel upstream versus downstream inside the pipe, and uses the time differential to figure the flow rate of the water in the pipe.

The NRC approved Vogtle's License Amendment Request (LAR) in March&nbsp;2008. The NRC staff determined that Southern Nuclear could safely increase the reactor's power output primarily through more accurate means of measuring feedwater flow. NRC staff also reviewed Southern Nuclear's evaluations showing that the plant's design can handle the increased power level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrc.gov/reading-rm/doc-collections/news/2008/08-043.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090512132415/http://www.nrc.gov/reading-rm/doc-collections/news/2008/08-043.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=May 12, 2009|title=NRC: News Release - 2008-043 - NRC Approves Power Uprate for Vogtle Nuclear Power Plant|date=May 12, 2009}}</ref> Unit&nbsp;1 was uprated during its Spring 2008 refueling outage, and Unit&nbsp;2 was uprated in the Fall outage of the same year.

